[Leptospermum sphaerocarpum]]'' <small>Cheel</small> - NSW  \n*''[[Leptospermum spinescens]]'' <small>[[Endl.]]</small> - WA\n*''[[Leptospermum squarrosum]]'' <small>Gaertn.</small> - NSW \n*''[[Leptospermum subglabratum]]'' <small>Joy Thomps.</small> - NSW \n*''[[Leptospermum subtenue]]'' <small>Joy Thomps.</small> - [[Western Australia|WA]] \n*''[[Leptospermum thompsonii]]'' <small>Joy Thomps.</small> - NSW  \n*''[[Leptospermum trinervium]]'' <small>(Sm.) Joy Thomps.</small> - Qld, NSW, Vic\n*''[[Leptospermum turbinatum]]'' <small>Joy Thomps.</small> - Vic\n*''[[Leptospermum variabile]]'' <small>Joy Thomps.</small> - Qld, NSW\n*''[[Leptospermum venustum]]'' <small>A.R.Bean</small> - Qld  \n*''[[Leptospermum whitei]]'' <small>Cheel</small> - Qld, NSW  \n*''[[Leptospermum wooroonooran]]'' <small>F.M.Bailey</small> - Qld\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category-inline}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q135621}}\n\n[[Category:Leptospermum| ]]\n[[Category:Myrtaceae genera]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Georg Forster]]\n", "text_old": "{{automatic taxobox\n|image = Leptospermum squarrosum.jpg\n|image_caption = ''Leptospermum squarrosum''\n|taxon = Leptospermum\n|authority = [[Johann Reinhold Forster|J.R.Forster]] & [[Georg Forster|G.Forster]]<ref name=\"APC\">{{cite web |title=''Leptospermum'' |url=https://biodiversity.org.au/nsl/services/search?product=APC&tree.id=51209179&name=Leptospermum&inc._scientific=&inc.scientific=on&inc._cultivar=&max=1000&display=apc&search=true|publisher=Australian Plant Census |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n|synonyms_ref = <ref name=\"APC\" />\n|synonyms = *''Glaphyria'' <small>[[William Jack (botanist)|Jack]]</small>\n*''Agonomyrtus'' <small>[[Johannes Conrad Schauer|Schauer]] ex [[Ludwig Reichenbach|Rchb.]]</small>\n*''Macklottia'' <small>[[Pieter Willem Korthals|Korth.]]</small>\n*''Leptospermopsis'' <small>[[Spencer Le Marchant Moore|S.Moore]]</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Leptospermum''''' {{IPAc-en|\u02cc|l|\u025b|p|t|\u0259|\u02c8|s|p|\u025c\u02d0r|m|\u0259m|,_|-|t|o\u028a|-}}{{refn|{{Dictionary.com|accessdate=2016-01-21|Leptospermum}}}}<ref>''Sunset Western Garden Book,'' 1995:606\u2013607</ref> is a [[genus]] of shrubs and small trees in the myrtle [[Family (biology)|family]] [[Myrtaceae]] commonly known as '''tea trees''', although this name is sometimes also used for some species of ''[[Melaleuca]]''. Most species are [[endemism|endemic]] to [[Australia]], with the greatest diversity in the south of the continent but some are [[Indigenous (ecology)|native]] to other parts of the world, including [[New Zealand]] and [[Southeast Asia]]. Leptospermums all have five conspicuous [[petal]]s and five groups of [[stamen]]s which alternate with the petals. There is a single [[Stigma (botany)#Style|style]] in the centre of the flower and the fruit is a woody [[Capsule (botany)|capsule]]. The first formal description of a leptospermum was published in 1776 by the [[Germans|German]] botanists [[Johann Reinhold Forster]] and his son [[Johann Georg Adam Forster]], but an unambiguous definition of individual species in the genus was not achieved until 1979. Leptospermums grow in a wide range of habitats but are most commonly found in moist, low-nutrient soils. They have important uses in [[horticulture]], in the production of honey and in [[floristry]].\n\n==Description==\nPlants in the genus ''Leptospermum'' range in size from prostrate shrubs to small trees and have fibrous, flaky or papery bark. The leaves are arranged alternately and are relatively small, rigid and often aromatic when crushed. The flowers may be solitary or in groups and have [[Bract#Bracteole|bracteoles]] and [[sepal]]s which in most species fall off as the flower opens. There are five spreading, conspicuous petals which are white, pink or red. There are many stamens which are usually shorter than the petals and in five groups opposite the stamens, although they often appear to not be grouped. A simple style usually arises from a small depression in the ovary which has from three to five sections in most species, each section containing a few to many [[ovule]]s. The fruit is a woody capsule which opens at the top to release the seeds, although in some species this does not occur until the plant, or the part of it, dies.<ref name=\"Wrigley\">{{cite book|last1=Wrigley|first1=John W.|last2=Fagg|first2=Murray|title=Bottlebrushes, paperbarks & tea trees, and all other plants in the Leptospermum alliance|date=1993|publisher=Angus & Robertson|location=Pymble, N.S.W.|isbn=978-0207168673|edition=1181\u2013183}}</ref><ref name=\"RBGS\">{{cite web|title=Genus ''Leptospermum''|url=http://plantnet.rbgsyd.nsw.gov.au/cgi-bin/NSWfl.pl?page=nswfl&lvl=gn&name=Leptospermum|publisher=Royal Botanic Gardens Sydney: plantnet|accessdate=21 February 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"ANPSA\">{{cite web|title=''Leptospermum'' and its Relatives - Background|url=http://anpsa.org.au/leptos1.html|publisher=Australian Native Plants Society (Australia)|accessdate=21 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Taxonomy and naming==\nThe first formal description of a leptospermum was published by Johann Reinhold Forster and Johann Georg Adam Forster in their 1776 book, ''Characteres Generum Plantarum''.<ref name=APNI>{{cite web|title=''Leptospermum''|url=https://id.biodiversity.org.au/instance/apni/493571|publisher=APNI|accessdate=21 February 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Forster\">{{cite book|last1=Forster|first1=Johann Reinhold|last2=Forster|first2=Johann Georg Adam|title=Characteres Generum Plantarum|date=1776|location=London|page=71|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/23365#page/87/mode/1up|accessdate=21 February 2017|publisher=Prostant apud B. White, T. Cadell, & P. Elmsly}}</ref> In 1876, [[George Bentham]] described twenty species, but noted the difficulty of discriminating between species. (\"The species are very difficult to discriminate.\") Of the species he named, only ten remain as valid.<ref name=\"Wrigley\" /><ref name=\"Benth.\">{{cite journal|last1=Bentham|first1=George|title=Orders XLVIII. Myrtaceae- LXII. Compositae|journal=Flora Australiensis|date=1867|volume=3|pages=100\u2013111|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/41807#page/108/mode/1up|accessdate=21 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1979, [[Barbara Briggs]] and [[Lawrence Alexander Sidney Johnson|Laurie Johnson]] published a classification of the family Myrtaceae in the Journal of the ''[[Linnean Society of New South Wales|Journal of the Linnean Society of New South Wales]]''. Although there have been revisions to their groupings, their paper allowed a systematic examination of species in the genus ''Leptospermum''.<ref name=\"Briggs\">{{cite journal|last1=Briggs|first1=Barbara Gillian|title=Evolution in the Myrtaceae - Evidence from inflorescence structure|journal=Proceedings of the Linnean Society of New South Wales|date=1979|volume=102|issue=4|pages=157\u2013256|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/34874217#page/187/mode/1up|accessdate=21 February 2017}}</ref> In 1989, [[Joy Thompson (botanist)|Joy Thompson]] published a complete revision of the genus.<ref name=\"Telopea\">{{cite journal|last1=Thompson|first1=Joy|date=1989|title=A revision of the genus ''Leptospermum'' (Myrtaceae)|journal=Telopea|volume=3|issue=3|pages=301\u2013449|doi=10.7751/telopea19894902}}</ref> In 2000, O'Brien ''et al.'' published yet another revision, using [[Maturase K|matK]]-based evidence to suggest that ''Leptospermum'' is [[Polyphyly|polyphyletic]], and should be split into persistent, Western non-persistent, and Eastern non-persistent fruiting plants, with ''Leptospermum spinescens'' as an outlier.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=O'Brien|first=Marcelle M.|last2=Quinn|first2=Christopher J.|last3=Wilson|first3=Peter G.|date=2000|title=Molecular systematics of the Leptospermum suballiance (Myrtaceae)|journal=Australian Journal of Botany|volume=48|issue=5|pages=621|doi=10.1071/bt99021|issn=0067-1924}}</ref> However, neither phylogeny has been universally accepted.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Thornhill|first=Andrew H.|last2=Ho|first2=Simon Y.W.|last3=K\u00fclheim|first3=Carsten|last4=Crisp|first4=Michael D.|date=December 2015|title=Interpreting the modern distribution of Myrtaceae using a dated molecular phylogeny|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|volume=93|pages=29\u201343|doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2015.07.007|pmid=26211451|issn=1055-7903}}</ref> Current estimates recognize about ninety species of ''Leptospermum''.<ref name=\"Wrigley\" />\n\nThe common name ''tea tree'' derives from the practice of early Australian settlers who soaked the leaves of several species in boiling water to make a [[herbal tea]].<ref name=\"ANBG\">{{cite web|title=Leptospermum - family Myrtaceae Commonly known as \"teatrees\"|url=http://www.anbg.gov.au/leptospermum/|publisher=Australian National Botanic Garden|accessdate=21 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nMost ''Leptospermum'' species are endemic to Australia where most are found in southern areas of the country. They are most common in moist nutrient-poor soils although they sometimes occupy other situations. ''[[Leptospermum laevigatum]]'' is usually found growing on beach sand and ''[[Leptospermum riparium|L. riparium]]'' growing in [[Tasmania]]n rainforest on the edges of rivers. ''[[Leptospermum amboinense]]'' extends from [[Queensland]] to Southeast Asia and three species, ''[[Leptospermum javanicum|L. javanicum]]'', ''[[Leptospermum parviflorum|L. parviflorum]]'' and ''[[Leptospermum recurvum|L. recurvum]]'' are endemic to southeast Asia. ''L. recurvum'' is only found on [[Mount Kinabalu]] in [[Sabah]]. ''[[Leptospermum scoparium]]'' is one of the most widespread in the genus and occurs in [[New South Wales]], [[Victoria, Australia|Victoria]], Tasmania and [[New Zealand]], where it is one of the most widespread and important native shrub species.<ref name=\"Wrigley\" /><ref name=\"Telopea\" /><ref name=\"RBGS(2)\">{{cite web|title=''Leptospermum scoparium''|url=http://plantnet.rbgsyd.nsw.gov.au/cgi-bin/NSWfl.pl?page=nswfl&lvl=sp&name=Leptospermum~scoparium|publisher=Royal Botanic Gardens Sydney; plantnet|accessdate=21 February 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"N.Z.\">{{cite journal|last1=Stephens|first1=Jonathan M.C.|last2=Molan|first2=Peter C.|last3=Clarkson|first3=Bruce D.|title=A review of ''Leptospermum scoparium'' (Myrtaceae) in New Zealand|journal=New Zealand Journal of Botany|date=January 2005|volume=43|issue=2|pages=431\u2013449|doi=10.1080/0028825X.2005.9512966}}</ref>\n\n==Ecology==\nIn Australia, ''Leptospermum'' species are sometimes used as food plants by the [[larva]]e of [[Hepialidae|hepialid]] [[moth]]s of the genus ''[[Aenetus]]'', including ''A. lewinii'' and ''A. ligniveren''. These burrow horizontally into the trunk then vertically down.\n\n==Uses==\n===Use in horticulture===\nMost ''Leptospermum'' species make desirable [[garden]] plants. The hardiest species (''L. lanigerum, L. liversidgei, L. polygalifolium, L. rupestre, L. scoparium'') are hardy to about {{convert|-8|C|F}} to {{convert|-10|C|F}}; others are sensitive to frost. They tolerate most soils, but many supplies specify ericaceous (i.e. lime-free) compost with good drainage and full sun. Established plants are [[drought]] tolerant. They are often found as hedge plants on the west coast of the [[United States]], and some species are popular for cultivation as [[bonsai]]. Many [[cultivar]]s exist.\n\n===Use in floristry===\nThese flowers are also grown in double cultivars and are used in floral designs. However, they do not last when out of water and the single flowers do not last when wired. The 'Pacific Beauty' (''Leptospermum poolgalifolium'') is a useful flower to use in large church-service bowls and function arrangements, however use of ''Leptospermum'' in corporate designs is less desirable as they dry and drop when subjected to heating and air conditioning.\n\n===Honey production===\nThe [[nectar]] from the flowers is harvested by [[bee]]s; this is used to make [[Leptospermum honey]]. Honey produced from Australian ''[[Leptospermum polygalifolium]]'', also known as jelly bush or the lemon-scented tea tree, has been found to contain up to 1750&nbsp;mg/kg of '[[methylglyoxal]]' (MGO), an antibacterial compound.<ref>[http://www.australiangeographic.com.au/journal/native-honey-a-sweet-antibacterial.htm/ Native honey a sweet antibacterial] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110306093531/http://www.australiangeographic.com.au/journal/native-honey-a-sweet-antibacterial.htm |date=2011-03-06 }}, ''Australian Geographic'', March 3, 2011.</ref> However, after neutralization of this compound, the honey retains bactericidal activity.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Kwakman PHS |author2=te Velde AA |author3=de Boer L |author4=Vandenbroucke-Grauls CMJE |author5=Zaat SAJ | title = Two major medicinal honeys have different mechanisms of bactericidal activity | journal = PLoS ONE | year = 2011 | volume = 6 | issue = 3 | pages = e17709 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0017709 | pmid = 21394213 | pmc = 3048876|bibcode=2011PLoSO...617709K }}</ref>  Methylglyoxal thus does not appear to be the main contributor to the antimicrobial and antibacterial activities.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Molan, P. | year = 2008 | title = An explanation of why the MGO level in manuka honey does not show the antibacterial activity | journal = New Zealand BeeKeeper | volume = 16 | issue = 4 | pages =  11\u201313 | url = http://researchcommons.waikato.ac.nz/handle/10289/2142}}</ref>\n\nThe nectar of ''[[Leptospermum scoparium|L. scoparium]]'' is collected by bees and the honey produced is collected and marketed as [[Manuka honey]].<ref name=\"NZMPI\">{{cite web |title=Growing and harvesting M\u0101nuka honey |url=https://www.mpi.govt.nz/growing-and-harvesting/honey-and-bees/manuka-honey/ |publisher=New Zealand Ministry for Primary Industries |accessdate=5 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Species==\nThe following is a list of species